President Joe Biden has proclaimed April 16 to April 24, 2022, as National Park Week in the United States. In his proclamation, he emphasizes the importance of national parks in preserving natural splendor, wildlife, and resources. He mentions the 150th anniversary of Yellowstone National Park, the world's first national park, and expresses his desire to protect and share the beauty of America's national parks. President Biden also highlights the "America the Beautiful" initiative, which aims to conserve 30 percent of the country's lands and waters by 2030. He mentions the Bipartisan Infrastructure Law and the Great American Outdoors Act, which provide funding for revitalizing national parks, addressing maintenance backlogs, and promoting environmental sustainability. The President emphasizes the importance of engaging with Tribal Nations and recognizing their history and connection to national parks. He also discusses efforts to advance equity, diversity, and inclusion by providing equitable access to natural resources and creating opportunities for underserved communities. President Biden acknowledges the role of national parks in promoting physical, mental, and social health, particularly during the COVID-19 pandemic. He encourages all Americans to connect with national parks, recreate responsibly, and enjoy the benefits of spending time in the natural world.